103
00:06:25.290 --> 00:06:29.250
The idea behind DMAP is simple. We use cell line models

104
00:06:29.310 --> 00:06:32.880
of human cancer. We try to represent the diversity,

105
00:06:32.990 --> 00:06:36.390
molecular and genetic diversity of cancer using thousands of

106
00:06:36.450 --> 00:06:36.990
models.

107
00:06:38.370 --> 00:06:42.350
And we do molecular profiling, omics, the

108
00:06:42.390 --> 00:06:44.630
same that one would do with a tumor biopsy.

109
00:06:45.210 --> 00:06:48.350
But because these are cell lines, we can also do drug sensitivity

110
00:06:48.390 --> 00:06:52.030
testing and identify the genes that are required for cell

111
00:06:52.090 --> 00:06:56.070
growth. We can then integrate these two layers of information, so

112
00:06:56.110 --> 00:06:59.770
we can directly link cancer vulnerabilities to the

113
00:06:59.850 --> 00:07:01.890
molecular alterations of the tumors.

114
00:07:02.370 --> 00:07:06.330
So this connection between human cancer through

115
00:07:06.370 --> 00:07:08.430
the models to a drug,

116
00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:10.890
is what DMAP was built for.

117
00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:16.420
Over the past 15 years or so, we have created this resource,

118
00:07:17.070 --> 00:07:20.990
which has been growing over time in both the number of dataset,

119
00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:24.970
the data types, and also the number of cancers that are represented.

120
00:07:25.850 --> 00:07:29.450
The datasets are all in one place and integrated.

121
00:07:29.510 --> 00:07:32.590
We put a lot of effort so all these dataset can talk to each other.

122
00:07:33.210 --> 00:07:36.850
And the data has been used for many use

123
00:07:36.910 --> 00:07:40.630
cases, including probably one of the most important one, to

124
00:07:40.770 --> 00:07:42.990
identify new targets for therapy.

125
00:07:43.770 --> 00:07:47.110
It has also been used to validate and equally important, to

126
00:07:47.170 --> 00:07:48.850
invalidate targets, which

127
00:07:49.690 --> 00:07:51.970
can save a lot of time and resources.

128
00:07:52.430 --> 00:07:55.510
It has used to guide drug discovery programs,

129
00:07:56.290 --> 00:08:00.090
identify dependencies in selected patient populations,

130
00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:04.390
biomarkers of response, and these are large scale datasets,

131
00:08:04.850 --> 00:08:08.430
so we can identify patterns. So DMAP has provide us a systems

132
00:08:08.490 --> 00:08:10.470
view of cancer biology.

133
00:08:12.570 --> 00:08:14.810
So now I'd like to tell you how we got here.

134
00:08:16.530 --> 00:08:20.410
So many things and people had to come together to build DMAP.

135
00:08:20.890 --> 00:08:24.290
First, we needed large collection of cell lines, and we needed them

136
00:08:24.370 --> 00:08:28.250
well-characterized. We needed to find way to find

137
00:08:28.329 --> 00:08:32.270
essential genes to determine which genes were essential in each

138
00:08:32.331 --> 00:08:35.990
of the cell lines. We needed to profile drug sensitivity

139
00:08:36.030 --> 00:08:37.970
profile across hundreds of models.

140
00:08:38.670 --> 00:08:40.890
We needed to build a computational infrastructure.

141
00:08:41.030 --> 00:08:44.201
We were creating large scale dataset. We wanted to integrate.

142
00:08:44.270 --> 00:08:47.870
Many of these datasets were new. Nobody had built them before, so we

143
00:08:48.250 --> 00:08:50.630
needed our methods, and we needed software.

144
00:08:50.740 --> 00:08:54.430
We needed a tool to share and be able to easily explore the

145
00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:58.030
data. But these didn't come together at once, and it wasn't

146
00:08:58.070 --> 00:09:00.690
designed like this. It came together over time.

147
00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:02.790
So I'll tell you a little bit of story.

148
00:09:02.850 --> 00:09:05.450
This took 15 years, so I'm going to try to do it justice.

149
00:09:07.010 --> 00:09:10.270
So very early days, when we were trying to model

150
00:09:10.370 --> 00:09:13.970
cancer, we were doing so by having three or

151
00:09:14.030 --> 00:09:16.830
four well-behaved cell lines that grow really well in the lab.

152
00:09:17.510 --> 00:09:19.950
Now we know cancer is highly heterogeneous.

153
00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:24.010
There's many tumor types, subtypes, molecular features, copy

154
00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:25.330
number changes, et cetera.

155
00:09:26.270 --> 00:09:28.650
Which I'm trying to illustrate here on the left.

156
00:09:28.750 --> 00:09:32.450
So we were trying to model what's on the left, with what's on the right,

157
00:09:32.810 --> 00:09:34.770
which was clearly a mismatch.

158
00:09:36.590 --> 00:09:39.610
So let me take a moment to talk about the NCI60.

159
00:09:39.670 --> 00:09:43.470
NCI60 was this collection of 60 cell lines that the NCI

160
00:09:43.510 --> 00:09:46.780
put together to do drug sensitivity testing, and it

161
00:09:46.830 --> 00:09:49.850
identify differential sensitivities across the cell line.

162
00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:54.210
Although these 60, it seems small, and it was

163
00:09:54.430 --> 00:09:58.050
small, nevertheless, it did provide the first hint that

164
00:09:58.090 --> 00:10:02.070
doing drug sensitivity profiling across different cell

165
00:10:02.130 --> 00:10:05.510
types representing different tumors could identify differential sensitivities.

166
00:10:05.910 --> 00:10:09.670
And in fact, the EGFR inhibitor sensitivity

167
00:10:10.650 --> 00:10:14.090
to EGFR mutant cell lines was discovered using

168
00:10:14.150 --> 00:10:15.090
this panel.

169
00:10:16.010 --> 00:10:18.170
But clearly that was not enough. It was

170
00:10:19.090 --> 00:10:22.410
relatively small. So Bill Sellers and Levi

171
00:10:22.570 --> 00:10:26.210
Garraway decided to change that and to dramatically

172
00:10:26.250 --> 00:10:30.190
expand the number of models. So they set up to do

173
00:10:30.750 --> 00:10:34.390
1,000 models, to collect those models, and then do profiling and drug

174
00:10:34.450 --> 00:10:38.309
sensitivity testing. That was a major undertaking at the

175
00:10:38.369 --> 00:10:42.130
time, and including now, just by collecting those 1,000 models.

176
00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:46.990
But Jordi Barretina and colleagues at the Broad

177
00:10:47.050 --> 00:10:50.570
Institute, as well as Novartis Oncology, did the

178
00:10:50.630 --> 00:10:54.490
work, and this is how the Cancer Cell Line Encyclopedia

179
00:10:54.530 --> 00:10:58.400
was born. It was a transformative project that has been used, I'm

180
00:10:58.450 --> 00:11:02.250
sure many of you know about CCLE, now is part of

181
00:11:02.310 --> 00:11:06.190
that map, and it has been helpful for cancer research,

182
00:11:06.270 --> 00:11:09.810
but also beyond, as well, to select

183
00:11:10.090 --> 00:11:13.810
models for the studies, but also other

184
00:11:13.870 --> 00:11:14.150
things.

185
00:11:15.950 --> 00:11:19.590
Now, around the same time, a technological

186
00:11:19.630 --> 00:11:23.330
breakthrough happened. That is the ability to do

187
00:11:23.390 --> 00:11:26.210
genome scale genetic perturbation screens.

188
00:11:26.550 --> 00:11:30.100
At a time this was using shRNA reagents that were coming

189
00:11:30.170 --> 00:11:30.630
online.

190
00:11:31.850 --> 00:11:35.510
And before that, if we wanted to test if a gene was

191
00:11:35.570 --> 00:11:39.390
essential for cell growth, we needed to knock down that gene with

192
00:11:39.490 --> 00:11:42.910
one shRNA or hopefully a few of them, and then

193
00:11:43.630 --> 00:11:45.910
test if that gene was killing the cells.

194
00:11:46.550 --> 00:11:50.130
And if we wanted to do the whole genome, we will have to repeat this 20,000

195
00:11:50.170 --> 00:11:51.990
times. When genome scale

196
00:11:53.350 --> 00:11:57.270
shRNA screens, in this case, were possible, now we could

197
00:11:57.350 --> 00:12:01.190
test all the genes in the genome at once in one experiment,

198
00:12:01.510 --> 00:12:02.290
where we could determine

199
00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:06.730
if they were required for cell growth very easily or

200
00:12:06.870 --> 00:12:07.410
easier.

201
00:12:08.390 --> 00:12:12.290
So Dave Root Lab and Bill Han and many

202
00:12:12.330 --> 00:12:15.690
other groups made this possible, and it has been

203
00:12:15.790 --> 00:12:19.410
really transformative. In fact, this is how genetic

204
00:12:19.750 --> 00:12:23.290
perturbation screens at scale startedNow,

205
00:12:23.950 --> 00:12:24.950
with this in hand,

206
00:12:26.070 --> 00:12:29.190
Bill Hahn decided to start Project Achilles.

207
00:12:29.770 --> 00:12:33.750
So the Project Achilles, the goal was to

208
00:12:33.770 --> 00:12:37.710
do genetic perturbation screens with shRNA

209
00:12:37.790 --> 00:12:41.470
in at least 100 lines. That was a major undertaking.

210
00:12:41.590 --> 00:12:45.570
Doing genome scale screens was not easy, was not

211
00:12:45.610 --> 00:12:46.550
as easy as doing

212
00:12:47.370 --> 00:12:49.910
an RNA-Seq, for instance. And

213
00:12:51.170 --> 00:12:55.150
the idea here was, if we were to do this, we could, one, compare

214
00:12:55.290 --> 00:12:58.970
genes to each other. We could know which of the genes that we're testing is

215
00:12:59.010 --> 00:13:01.170
better at killing the cells versus others.

216
00:13:01.690 --> 00:13:05.410
And we could also know, importantly, which gene were killing all the cell lines

217
00:13:05.450 --> 00:13:08.650
that were turning to be pan-essential, that would not make them

218
00:13:09.130 --> 00:13:13.120
particularly good drug targets, and which of those

219
00:13:13.170 --> 00:13:14.370
were more selective.

220
00:13:15.410 --> 00:13:18.630
So Jesse Boehm brought the team together,

221
00:13:19.210 --> 00:13:19.490
and

222
00:13:20.390 --> 00:13:24.220
Barbara Wier, here in the room, she was the lead computational

223
00:13:24.330 --> 00:13:27.850
scientist for the project. And Glenn Cowley

224
00:13:28.350 --> 00:13:32.010
made the largest scale screen possible at a

225
00:13:32.030 --> 00:13:35.270
scale that no one could imagine that it could be done.

226
00:13:39.430 --> 00:13:43.190
But shRNA, unfortunately, wasn't as good

227
00:13:43.370 --> 00:13:47.310
as we would've liked it, although we are still using shRNA data, so it's

228
00:13:47.350 --> 00:13:51.250
definitely useful. But nevertheless, a few years later,

229
00:13:51.470 --> 00:13:55.070
Feng Zhan was working on CRISPR, and

230
00:13:55.650 --> 00:13:59.590
we knew the technology was transformative, so we invited Feng to

231
00:13:59.650 --> 00:14:02.210
one of our Achilles meetings. And

232
00:14:03.170 --> 00:14:06.910
after that meeting, we started a transition from RNAi to

233
00:14:06.970 --> 00:14:10.050
CRISPR. We did a pilot screen,

234
00:14:10.610 --> 00:14:14.250
and we did a comparison between

235
00:14:14.270 --> 00:14:17.910
shRNA and CRISPR, and it was clear that

236
00:14:19.030 --> 00:14:22.810
with CRISPR, we could separate better the genes that were essential

237
00:14:22.830 --> 00:14:25.960
versus not essential. This is what I'm showing in this graph, where I'm showing the

238
00:14:26.030 --> 00:14:28.690
distributions, in blue of the

239
00:14:31.430 --> 00:14:33.349
non-essential, in red of the essential.

240
00:14:33.430 --> 00:14:35.990
At the bottom is shRNA, and the top is CRISPR.

241
00:14:36.050 --> 00:14:39.850
You can see how much better separated the distributions are in

242
00:14:39.890 --> 00:14:43.130
CRISPR versus shRNA. So these allow us to identify

243
00:14:43.170 --> 00:14:46.670
significantly more gene dependencies with CRISPR.

244
00:14:48.830 --> 00:14:51.110
Now, as we were building these data sets,

245
00:14:52.050 --> 00:14:52.370
we

246
00:14:53.210 --> 00:14:56.750
realized we needed to start building a computational infrastructure.

247
00:14:57.030 --> 00:15:00.970
We wanted to integrate the data. Many of these data sets were unique.

248
00:15:01.050 --> 00:15:04.990
Nobody had built the large scale shRNA data set before,

249
00:15:05.020 --> 00:15:07.570
and nobody has integrated the data.

250
00:15:07.710 --> 00:15:11.470
So we needed new computational tools. We need a pipeline.

251
00:15:11.510 --> 00:15:15.419
We need a software. So Abhijit Czerniak founded the Cancer

252
00:15:15.490 --> 00:15:16.240
Data Science,

253
00:15:17.150 --> 00:15:20.240
with the purpose of this, building a computational

254
00:15:20.330 --> 00:15:23.930
infrastructure for the map that we can

255
00:15:23.990 --> 00:15:27.650
use to make use of all of this data. And

256
00:15:27.910 --> 00:15:30.350
this team has grown over the years.

257
00:15:30.750 --> 00:15:34.550
It has evolved in parallel as we have been evolving

258
00:15:34.570 --> 00:15:37.490
them up with new data sets and growing.

259
00:15:38.170 --> 00:15:41.990
And Jay McFarlane, after Abhijit, took it

260
00:15:42.050 --> 00:15:45.070
further. He built additional computational methods,

261
00:15:45.730 --> 00:15:49.590
and Katharina Kampert now leads it, bringing her own

