00:16:57.010 --> 00:17:00.870
proved that the concept was right,

283
00:17:01.110 --> 00:17:05.110
that we could map systematically and link systematically these

284
00:17:05.131 --> 00:17:07.450
dependencies to molecular features.

285
00:17:08.391 --> 00:17:09.931
But there was a lot of work to be done.

286
00:17:11.750 --> 00:17:14.970
Now, until here, we were still missing drug sensitivity.

287
00:17:16.070 --> 00:17:19.891
We had a little bit of data, but we didn't have data at a scale that we

288
00:17:19.950 --> 00:17:23.770
needed. So doing drug sensitivity tested across

289
00:17:24.330 --> 00:17:28.230
many cell lines, never mind across hundreds, I'm sure

290
00:17:28.290 --> 00:17:30.730
you realize that it's very time-consuming, expensive.

291
00:17:30.810 --> 00:17:32.830
You have to thaw each of these lines.

292
00:17:32.870 --> 00:17:36.290
You have to test the drug sensitivity. You have to freeze it back.

293
00:17:36.890 --> 00:17:40.870
And this takes a long time. So to Gallup, and Channing

294
00:17:40.910 --> 00:17:44.470
Woo was working in his lab at the time, invented this

295
00:17:44.510 --> 00:17:48.400
technology, prism. And the idea was that each of the cell

296
00:17:48.430 --> 00:17:51.170
lines could be labeled with a DNA barcode.

297
00:17:51.670 --> 00:17:54.130
Once the cell lines are labeled, they could be pooled together.

298
00:17:55.270 --> 00:17:58.770
So now once they are in pool, you could test their drug sensitivity,

299
00:17:59.210 --> 00:18:02.730
and they convolute the data by identifying the abundance of the

300
00:18:02.770 --> 00:18:06.040
barcode pre and post-treatment. So this was

301
00:18:06.070 --> 00:18:08.970
successful, and they built an assay.

302
00:18:09.390 --> 00:18:11.890
This assay, early days, was not very high throughput.

303
00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:15.810
It was an academic assay. But Jen Roth and her

304
00:18:15.870 --> 00:18:19.050
team over the years have really made this assay

305
00:18:19.090 --> 00:18:22.926
transformative.They have taken this assay and

306
00:18:22.986 --> 00:18:26.786
made it an industry standard, very reproducible, very high

307
00:18:26.886 --> 00:18:30.836
quality data that now hundreds of companies are using

308
00:18:30.836 --> 00:18:31.866
to test their drugs.

309
00:18:33.966 --> 00:18:37.226
But in addition to that, now it does provide us an

310
00:18:37.266 --> 00:18:40.886
opportunity to include drug sensitivity data in

311
00:18:41.026 --> 00:18:44.446
Demap, and we are currently testing all the newer sort of

312
00:18:44.486 --> 00:18:45.706
therapeutics

313
00:18:46.726 --> 00:18:49.446
that have been released in the past few years.

314
00:18:49.466 --> 00:18:51.266
Bill is going to talk a little bit more about this.

